    <p>
      As you may have already noticed in working through the exercises,
      since the six trigonometric ratios are all defined in terms of the three sides of a right triangle,
      there are several relationships between them.
      In <xref ref="rtidentityfirst">Exercises</xref>
      - <xref ref="rtidentitylast"></xref>,
      use the diagram on <xref ref="righttranglediagram">page</xref> along with <xref ref="righttrianglesinecosinetangent">Definitions</xref>
      and <xref ref="righttriangletherest"></xref>
      to show the following relationships hold for all acute angles.<fn>
      These are called trigonometric <em>identities</em>
      and will be studied in greater detail in <xref ref="FundamentalTrigonometricIdentities">Section</xref>.
      </fn>
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="rtidentityfirst">
          <p>
            <m>\tan(\theta) = \dfrac{\sin(\theta)}{\cos(\theta)}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\csc(\theta) = \dfrac{1}{\sin(\theta)}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sec(\theta) = \dfrac{1}{\cos(\theta)}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      For <xref ref="rtcofunctionfirst">Exercises</xref>
      - <xref ref="rrcofunctionlast"></xref>,
      it may be helpful to recall that
      <m>90^{\circ} - \theta</m> is the measure of the <sq>other</sq> acute angle in the right triangle besides <m>\theta</m>.
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="rtcofunctionfirst">
          <p>
            <m>\cos(\theta) = \sin\left( 90^{\circ} - \theta \right)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\csc(\theta) = \sec\left( 90^{\circ} - \theta \right)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="rrcofunctionlast">
          <p>
            <m>\cot(\theta) = \tan\left( 90^{\circ} - \theta \right)</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      For <xref ref="rtpythexercisefirst">Exercises</xref>
      - <xref ref="rtpythexerciselast"></xref>,
      it may be helpful to remember that <m>a^2+b^2 = c^2</m>:
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="rtpythexercisefirst">
          <p>
            <m>(\cos(\theta))^2 + (\sin(\theta))^2 = 1</m>
